The paper focuses on developing a data visualization framework for exploratory analysis of bipartite datasets, which involves human interaction with data through graphical representation. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with similarity representation and knowledge discovery, which are common themes in Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Data Mining (cs.DB) sub-categories. The paper also mentions benchmarking using datasets related to social groups, voting records, and global cuisine, which suggests that it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories.
